title: Grateful Dead Live at William and Mary College Hall on 1973-09-11
lineage: AUD>?>7" Reel @ 3.75 ips, No NR Technics RS-1506>hd-p2 24/96>CD Wav>Adobe Audition 2.0>flac Transferred/Seeded by Rob Berger 01.28.2011
description:
Set 1

Promised Land, Sugaree, The Race is On, Loser, Looks Like Rain, Tennessee Jed, Jack Straw, China Cat Sunflower-> I Know You Rider, El Paso, Mississippi Half Step, Playin' In The Band

Set 2

Let Me Sing*, Weather Report Suite Prelude*-> Weather Report Suite Part 1-> Let It Grow*, Row Jimmy, Big River, Deal, Beat It On Down The Line, Dark Star-> Morning Dew, Sugar Magnolia

*with Martin Fiero and Joe Ellis on horns. Doug Sahm opened; First Let Me Sing

reviews.review_text:
great job-thank you This show sent me into orbit today... ChinaRider thru halfstep had me in some other dimension..
335 into Row Jimmy, Jerry sing "Row Johnny" -first i had heard that. The Dark Star-Dew has a fantastic ending with jerry fanning his guitar...
Seriously good Epic show and super recording. Thank you to all who brought it to the Archive!

Seasons round, creatures great and small, up and down, as we rise and fall Flowing, mind-altering, beautiful music from one of my favorite GD periods. It's been fun comparing "eras" lately, partly spurred on by Blair Jackson's blog post here: http://bit.ly/LqA2Nc

Dusborne Bombs! Dusborne is my new hero of the matrix wizards.  He must by a Phil Phreak like me since all of his matrices have loud signals and louder Phil!  This is a fantastic combo of audience and soundboard.  As far the music goes, the ‘Playin’ is one of my favorite ever.  Weir’s work on ‘China Cat Sunflower’ at this time is great and this one is no exception.  With this mix, the Martin Fiero stuff is a LOT more enjoyable.  The ‘Dark Star’ is downright mystical.  The 'Morning Dew' is a uncharacteristic bummer due to change in signal and Garcia’s guitar being completely out of tune. Despite his “sloppy” reputation, I’ve always regarded Garcia as the consummate professional guitar player and his efforts at tuning while starting the 'Dew' puts a grin on my face, to be sure.  Five for the music and mix.

5star let it grow amazing even among other martian feiro versions from 73/74  silky smooth and well recourded china cat also
6/22/73 pne a bit finer in some audio respects

One of the best-mixed MTXs I've heard It's also the first really hot show of the '73 fall tour. The ending jam is short but consists of a fine, fine Dark Star > Morning Dew. Also the first really good Sing Your Blues Away, and lots of other hot renditions.

church The Dead is like church to me. I wake up every morning and listen to a show and smoke a few bowls. Nothing prepares me for the day and fills me with the right kind of energy like they do. I never got to see a Dead show (I was born in 1988), but these shows on Archive have brought me into their magical world.

This show, in particular, is a wonderful church service - the horns are pitch perfect and this matrix captures them perfectly. This "Playing" is especially electric.

Atmospheric This is a gloriously atmospheric recording of a show that has tons of the X-factor. Novice listeners would need to be patient with it, so have it on with some time on your hands, and let it sink in. Classic show from the Golden Era of the Grateful Dead.

minor correction Dusborne matrixes are the current gold standard for this type of work; I'm a strong amateur-matrix skeptic overall, and find most of them unlistenable, but his mixes are reliably good to great and this is no exception. 

I note for the record that this is NOT the debut of Let Me Sing Your Blues Away; that was just prior, at 9.8.73 Nassau.

The show itself is a fine to very good example from the era, perhaps the best from this tour, which I find rather uninspired for the year. I'm a big fan of '73 Dead overall, but the horns tour just doesn't do it for me. This show is pretty much the exception, and the next night to a lesser degree.
